<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-396-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 396 650.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  May 1 1990 v4 n17 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PCPC rolls out 2-way color monitor, SE/30 cards. (PersonalComputer Peripherals Corp.) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Norr, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Personal Computer Peripherals Corp. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Personal Computer Peripherals Flipper (Monitor, color) (productintroduction)Personal Computer Peripherals PCPC CGC/SE 30/16 (Graphics board)(product introduction)Personal Computer Peripherals PCPC CGC/SE 30/8 (Graphics board)(product introduction).andO;Topic:     Graphics Boards-CardsMonitorsProduct Introduction.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Henry NorrandM;San Francisco -- Just weeks after Radius Inc. unveiled the Pivot, itsrotating monochrome monitor, Personal Computer Peripherals Corp. last monthshowed a color display that also works in either landscape or portrait modebut without the Pivot's on-the-fly reorientation capabilities.andM;PCPC also introduced new color display boards for the Mac SE/30 and announcedshipment of a new generation of &quot;flicker-free&quot; cards for the Mac II family.andM;Called The Flipper, PCPC's entry in the emerging dual-orientation displayfield is a 17-inch custom monitor with 72 dpi and a refresh rate of 72 Hz.andO;The $2,495 display system, expected to ship this month, includes an eight-bitcolor display card for the SE/30 or the Mac II family.andP;  A 16-bit colorversion will cost $2,995.andM;While The Flipper, like Radius' Pivot, works in either landscape or portraitmode, the PCPC system does not automatically reorient the Mac desktop whenthe monitor is rotated; the user must reboot each time the orientation ischanged.andM;The Flipper will ship later this month, according to the company.andM;The company also unveiled several display boards for standard color monitors:andM;andgt;Eight- and 16-bit color boards for the Mac SE/30.andP;  The CGC/SE 30/16, capableof displaying nearly 33,000 colors, is priced at $1,479, or at $2,979 with a20-inch Ikegami Trinitron monitor.andP;  It supports resolutions of 1,024 by 768pixels or 640 by 480 pixels at 72 dpi with a refresh rate of 75 Hz.andM;The CGC/SE 30/8, an eight-bit version of the board, is priced at $979.andP;  Itcan be upgraded to 16-bit color for $979.andM;While several other display vendors offer SE/30 color systems, one of thefirst to offer color for the compact Mac, SuperMac Technology of Sunnyvale,Calif., recently decided to end active marketing of its SE/30 cards.andP;  Acompany representative cited slow sales.andM;andgt;PCPC's CGC II Series, a new generation of eight- and 32-bit NuBus colorcards offering a flicker-free 75-Hz refresh rate on large-screen displays.andO;The eight-bit version is priced at $779, the 32-bit board at $1,979, andupgrades from eight to 32 bits at $1,479.andP;  The eight-bit board is alsoavailable in a $3,658 bundle with either a 19-inch Sony Trinitron or a21-inch Hitachi monitor; the 32-bit card with either monitor is $4,858.andM;PCPC is at 4710 Eisenhower Blvd., Building A-4, Tampa, Fla.andP;  33634; (813)884-3092; (800) 622-2888.andO;</TEXT></DOC>